    "text": "CHAPTER 01\nWELCOME\nTO THE WASTELAND\n“Welcome to Nuka-World, New Meat!\nYou ready to throw down with some of\nthe meanest, nastiest SOBs this side of the\nWasteland? Sad t’say it doesn’t really matter,\n‘cause out here, nobody got nothin’ and everyone\nwants what everyone else has. So, if you ain’t prepared to\ndefend what you got, you ain’t gonna have nothin’ left.\nI know the place looks all jolly and fun, but behind those big\nsmilin’ faces are bloodthirsty Raiders the likes o’ which the\nWasteland is glad are holed up in here. Disciples, Operators\nand The Pack, all of ’em want to rule the roost. It’s only the\nconstant fightin’ that keeps ‘em all in check – new Butchers\nare always lookin’ to climb to the top of the corpse pile,\nadding to it as they go. So, I guess the only question left is: you\ngonna be the one climbin’, or the one bein’ climbed over?”\n05\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 01: Welcome to the Wasteland"
  },
  {
    "page": 6,
    "text": "06\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 01: Welcome to the Wasteland\nWARGAMING 101\nIs this your first wargame? If so, you’re in for a treat!\nIn this ever-growing hobby, players build collections of miniature\nfigures and send them to battle across boards filled with detailed\nscenery pieces. There’s a huge variety of tabletop wargames out\nthere, each based around a specific setting, some fictional, some\nhistorical. In Fallout: Factions ‘Nuka-World’, you can recreate the\nworld of the Fallout video game series, specifically the Nuka-World\nexpansion for Fallout 4.\nYou will gather a collection of models (around ten of them)\nto represent your crew of dangerous fighters, choosing from\nthe various groups that are vying for control of the derelict\nNuka-World theme park. You and an opponent clash across a\n3D battlefield, where your models clamber through rubble and\nwreckage, exchanging fire across ruined amphitheatres and\nbetween the stalled cars of abandoned rides.\nA game lasts around an hour for new players, but will usually\ntake less time once you have some experience under your belt.\nCOLLECTING MINIATURES\nFallout: Factions is played with 28mm tall plastic figures, which\nthe rules refer to as “models”. Each player needs a set of around\nten miniatures before they can play.\nThis starter set contains enough miniatures to\ncreate two crews - one from the Pack faction and\none from the Operators. Assembly instructions for\nboth crews can be found at www.modiphius.net.\nBefore assembling your models, you should read through the\nfirst couple of chapters of this book and figure out how the game\nworks. Most Fallout: Factions models can be assembled in a\nnumber of different ways, and you should wait until you can\nmake an informed decision before you choose which ones to go for!\nPainting models is an optional but highly recommended part of\nthe hobby. It allows players to personalize their crew, whether\nthey want to match the look of the Fallout video games, or try\nsomething entirely unique. Painting guides and advice can be\nfound at www.modiphius.net (Use the QR code above).\nAN ONGOING NARRATIVE\nA single game of Fallout: Factions is only part of the bigger\npicture. Each crew has its own story to tell, and you’ll follow your\ncrew’s ascent to glory (or descent into ruin) over the course of\nmultiple games.\nAs a crew plays more games, its members become experienced,\nincreasingly proficient, and pick up new abilities. They might also\nsuffer long-term injuries that impact future games - or could even\nbe killed outright!\nThis ongoing narrative is tracked for each crew separately, so you\ndon’t have to stick with the same group of gamers throughout\nyour crew’s story – although many players find that is a more\nsatisfying way to play.\nWelcome to Nuka-World! Before we get started, let’s talk about\nhow this book is laid out.\nIt’s split into two sections: the Game Rules (four chapters, starting\nwith this one) and the Game Reference (four appendices).\nYou’ll read the Game Rules section when you’re learning how\nto play, and you may come back to check individual rules\nlater. The Game Reference section contains information that\nyou may need to look up during play, so you’ll use it less when\nlearning, but refer to it before, during and after games."
  },
  {
    "page": 7,
    "text": "07\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 01: Welcome to the Wasteland\nThis section details the components that you need to play a\ngame of Fallout: Factions. This Fallout: Factions - Battle for\nNuka-World Starter set contains:\n★\t80-Page Rulebook x1\n★\tInitiative / Retreat Token x1\n★\t1 Harm / 2 Harm Tokens x24\n★\t3 Harm / 4 Harm Tokens x6\n★\tWeary / Exhausted Tokens x30\n★\tSearch Tokens / Radiation Tokens x8\n★\tObjective Tokens x6\n★\tPloy Tokens x6\n★\tRound Tracker Tokens x5\n★\tTen-sided Standard Dice x8\n★\tTen-sided Luck Dice x4\n★\tSprue of The Pack Miniatures x1\n★\tSprue of The Operators Miniatures x1\n★\tSheets of Punch out Terrain x2\n★\tTape Measure x1\n★\t3'x2' Battle Map / Poster x1\n★\tBlank Crew Sheet x2\nEach player also needs a printed Crew Roster, a pencil, and an\neraser. Crew Rosters can be downloaded at www.modiphius.net,\nor photocopied from pg 73.\nGAME COMPONENTS\nharm tokens\nweary / exhausted tokens\nsearch / radiation tokens\ncrew roster\nTerrain sheets\nmeasuring tape\nrulebook\nbattle map\nInitiative token\nround tracker tokens\nobjective tokens\nThe pack\nminiatures\nThe operators\nminiatures\nPloy tokens\nStandard dice\nluck dice"
