    "page": 8,
    "text": "08\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nBottle: Hey folks! I’m Bottle …\nCappy: … and I’m Cappy! We’re so glad you’ve joined us here at Nuka-World!\nAmerica’s favorite vacation destination!\nBottle: If you wanna have F-U-N, there are a few rules you need to follow.\nRule No. 1:\nBe a Good Sport!\nCappy: It’s easy to get carried away when you’re playing head-to-head against\nyour friends.\nBottle: Or anyone else, for that matter!\nCappy: But remember, the only real way to win is to make sure your opponent\nis having as much fun as you are.\nBottle: …and to achieve your mission objectives before they do!\nCappy: Kinda stepping on my point there, Bottle!\nBottle: Whoops! Sorry.\nRule No. 2:\nUse Your Noggin!\nCappy: There’s a lot happening in a game of Fallout: Factions, and there’s\na chance that you might find yourself in a situation where the rules don’t quite\ncover every eventuality.\nBottle: Oh no!\nCappy: No need to panic, Bottle! If this happens, just use some good\nold-fashioned common sense and decide on what should happen.\nBottle: But Cappy, what if you can’t decide?\nCappy: Roll a die, flip a coin, or ask a friend. The important thing is to keep\nit moving, and not let the game get bogged down! You can always do some\nin-depth research once the action’s over.\nRule No. 3:\nNo Cheating!\nBottle: … Uh, Cappy, do we really need to say this one out loud?\nCappy: You’d be surprised, Bottle!\nBottle: Well, okay then. No cheating, folks!\nCappy: It would be super easy to fudge a few numbers on your Crew Roster\nbetween games, but ask yourself … who are you really cheating?\nBottle: If you ever feel tempted, just take a big breath, have a sip of cool,\nrefreshing Nuka-Cola, and make the right call.\nCappy: We know you can do it!\nPARK RULES\n08\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 01: Welcome to the Wasteland"
  },
  {
    "page": 9,
    "text": "09\nCHAPTER 02\nBUILDING\nBLOCKS\n“So, you wanna do the climbin’ then?\nGood choice, New Meat - always better\nto be the one doin’ the stompin’ than\nthe one being stomped, right? But if yer\nserious, yer gonna need a helpin’ hand to get\nstarted. Ah, don’t worry, I don’t charge much - and what’s\nyer life worth anyway? Stick with me and I’ll show you how\nto get some bodies between you and the bullets, give ya a\nlay of the land, teach ya the finer points of ‘Raiderin’, and\nmake sure you come out on top. Trust me, there ain’t no one\nbetter in this business than me.”\n09\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks"
  },
  {
    "page": 10,
    "text": "10\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nBuilding\nshack\nbus\nDesigner’s Note: Surveying Scenery\nMAJOR TERRAIN FEATURES\nTHE BATTLEFIELD\nA game of Fallout: Factions always takes place on a flat rectangular\nsurface measuring two feet by three feet, and populated with Terrain\nFeatures. This is referred to as the Battlefield.\nAll of the action in a game happens within the Battlefield. Models\ncannot be placed so that any part of their Base is outside the\nlimits of the Battlefield, and unless a rule specifically states\notherwise, a model cannot move off the Battlefield.\nTERRAIN FEATURES\nA Battlefield should never be a large, open space. Fallout: Factions\nis a much more interesting game when it is played across an\nevocative Battlefield with a variety of Terrain Features that\nmodels can take cover behind and manuever around.\nAs every player’s Terrain collection is different, there are no\nhard and fast rules for defining Terrain Features. Instead, the\nrules refer to three broad categories: Major Features, Minor\nFeatures and Decorative Features.\nMAJOR TERRAIN FEATURES\nThese are large pieces of Terrain which dominate an area of the\nBattlefield. Examples include: buildings, large vehicles, industrial\nwalkways, and large rock piles.\nThe purpose of Major Features is to break up the Battlefield,\nobscuring sight lines and creating bottlenecks that influence each\ncrew’s movement. As such, Major Features should block line of\nsight to some degree – a model standing on one side should not\nbe able to see a model standing on the other side, or should at the\nvery least have a significantly obstructed view.\nMajor Features may have multiple levels, and models may be able\nto move around on top of them.\nIf a Terrain collection features multiple Minor Features arranged\non a single Base, this could also be treated as a Major Feature.\nAn average Battlefield should usually have between four and six\nMajor Terrain Features, but this varies depending on their size.\nThis chapter features all of the core rules for playing a game\nof Fallout: Factions. It doesn’t cover choosing Scenarios, or\nsetting up and linking games with the Story Phase – these are\ncovered in later chapters..\nBefore setting up to play a game, it is helpful if you and\nyour opponent take a moment to look at the Terrain that’s\navailable to you and agree on how each piece should be\ncategorized. You should also briefly discuss any other\nquestions that might come up – can a model move through\nthe doors on this building, even though they’re modeled\nas being closed? Can models see and attack through that\nchain-link fence? Can a model squeeze through that gap?\nYou’re unlikely to cover every eventuality in advance, but a\nshort chat before starting can head off a lot of sticking points.\nIf something else comes up during play, let the Park Rules\n(pg. 8) be your guide!"
  },
  {
    "page": 11,
    "text": "11\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nMINOR TERRAIN FEATURES\nMINOR TERRAIN FEATURES\nThese are smaller pieces of Terrain which are used to break up\nthe open ground between Major Terrain Features. Examples\ninclude: walls and barricades, small vehicles, vending machines,\nand dumpsters.\nThe purpose of Minor Features is to add further texture to the\nBattlefield, reducing the number of open areas and giving players\nopportunities to tuck their models behind cover.\nFor each Major Feature on a Battlefield, there should be two to\nfour Minor Features, depending on their size.\nDECORATIVE TERRAIN FEATURES\nFor many players, creating an evocative Battlefield is as much\nfun as playing a game. This category exists for those people, and\nincludes features such as piles of rubble, toppled furniture, or\nfallen branches.\nDecorative Features are small and insignificant, and are entirely\nignored by the rules. If a Decorative Feature is ever in the way of\na model, it can be moved aside, or removed entirely.\nAs Decorative Features have no effect on the game, there is no\nlimit to how many should be used – they are simply a chance\nfor players to express their creativity and build an evocative\nWasteland diorama at the start of a game!\nbenches\nbarrels\nmap sign\ncrates\nwalls & Barricades\ngraves"
  },
