    "page": 13,
    "text": "13\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nS\nStrength measures the model’s raw physical power. It is mainly\nused when making attacks with Melee and Heavy weapons.\nP\nPerception measures the model’s awareness of the Battlefield.\nIt is mainly used when firing Rifles, but it is also used by some\nspecial Scenario rules.\nE\nEndurance measures the model’s stamina and physical\ntoughness. It is mainly used when the model is the Target of an\nattack, to see whether it is Harmed.\nC\nCharisma measures the model’s natural charm and\nleadership. It is mainly used when determining which allies can\nsupport a model’s Actions.\nI\nIntelligence measures the model’s knowledge, wisdom, and\nwit. It is mainly used to see whether a model can be trusted\nto follow the plan and stick around, or flee when the shooting\nstarts. It is also used when models interact with certain\nBattlefield features.\nA\nAgility measures the model’s coordination and\nmaneuverability. It is mainly used when attacking with Pistols\nand Grenades, or when climbing up or down Terrain.\nL\nLuck measures how lucky the model is. A higher Luck increases\na model’s chances of success across the board.\nMODEL CLASS EXAMPLE (OPERATOR CHAMPION AND GRUNT)\nMODEL CLASSES\nWhen choosing models for their crew, a player consults the\nModel Classes section of their Faction List. This section shows\nthe different types of models that are available to that Faction.\nEach Class shows:\na) Its name and whether it is a Champion or a Grunt.\nb) Its S.P.E.C.I.A.L. profile.\nc) Any Perks the model begins with.\nd) A selection of Weapon Sets that the model can be armed with.\nCHAMPIONS AND GRUNTS\nEach Class is either a Champion or a Grunt.\nChampions form the crew’s experienced core. They are good\nall-round fighters and can be relied upon to get the job done, but\nthere are only a few of them in each crew.\nThe rest of the crew is made up of Grunts, who are less effective\none-on-one, but make up for it with greater numbers. They often\nare best used to support a Champion’s actions.\nBOSS (CHAMPION, LEADER)\nPerks\n\n★ Natural Leader (Innate)\nWeapon Sets\n\n★ Marksman’s Handmade Rifle (44)\n\n★ Combat Rifle (50)\n\n★ Plasma Pistol and Shishkebab (51)\nPSYCHO (GRUNT)\nWeapon Sets\nNo more than three Psychos in a crew can have the same\nWeapon Set.\n\n★ 10mm Pistol (15)\n\n★ Combat Shotgun (17)\n\n★ 10mm Pistol and Hand Weapon (21)\nS\nP\nE\nC\nI\nA\nL\n♥\n5\n6\n5\n5\n6\n5\n3\n3\nS\nP\nE\nC\nI\nA\nL\n♥\n4\n4\n4\n3\n4\n4\n2\n1\nS.P.E.C.I.A.L. PROFILE\nEach Class has its own S.P.E.C.I.A.L. profile. This is a set of seven\nstatistics, each of which has a numerical value – the higher the\nvalue, the more proficient the model is in that area.\nIn addition to these seven statistics, each Class also has a\nHealth value (usually between 1 and 3), which shows how\nmany Injuries it can sustain during a game before being\nremoved from play.\nB\nB\nC\nD\nD"
  },
  {
    "page": 14,
    "text": "14\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nHANDMADE RIFLE\nTYPE\nTEST\nTRAITS\nCRITICAL EFFECT\nPARTS\nRAITING\nRifle (18\")\n4P\nFast\nSuppress (2)\n“Nothin’ as personal as killin’\nsomeone with a gun you made\nyerself. Tinkering with one of these\nbad boys is every Raider’s second\nfavorite hobby.”\nOn most commercially available ten-sided dice (often\nreferred to as D10s), the “10” face is marked with a “0”.\nNewcomers to polyhedral dice may find this a little strange\nat first, but once you get used to the fact that you can’t roll\na zero value, you’ll be fine!\nThe dice included in this box have a special icon in place of\nthe 1, provided to us by our good friends Bottle & Cappy!\nThis starter set contains eight Standard Dice and four\nLuck Dice. You can purchase additional sets of dice from\nwww.modiphius.net or anywhere that sells gaming dice.\nMore is always better!\nIf you ever find yourself in a situation where you don’t have\nenough dice for a roll you need to make, roll as many as you\nhave, note the result, then roll the rest.\nDesigner’s Note: on dice\nA model’s statistics are rated from 1 to 9, with a higher\nnumber representing more proficiency. For the first six\n(Strength to Agility), a value of 4 should be considered\nroughly average for a standard human character, so a model\nwith Perception 3 isn’t a great shot with a rifle, and a model\nwith Agility 6 is incredibly well-coordinated.\nLuck is a little different, with an average value of 2. Good\nfortune is hard to come by in the Wasteland!\nDesigner’s Note: Understanding\nS.P.E.C.I.A.L.\nPERKS\nPerks are special rules that apply to a model. These can be gained\nover time as the crew plays more games, but some models have a\nPerk or two to begin with. For example, most Factions have a Class\nwith the Natural Leader Perk, representing that they’ve managed\nto pull together enough bodies to form a crew of their own.\nWEAPON SETS\nWhen a player chooses a model for their crew, they must choose\none of the Weapon Sets available to its Class. The Weapon Set\nchosen should match the weapons carried by the miniature itself.\nEach Weapon Set also shows a number in parentheses. This is\nthe Rating for a model of that Class armed with that specific\nWeapon Set. Rating is a measure of the model’s power level in\nthe game – the higher the Rating, the more useful the model is.\nWEAPON PROFILES\nEach type of weapon in Fallout: Factions has its own Profile, just\nlike each Model Class. A Weapon’s Profile is used whenever the\nmodel makes an attack with that weapon. Note that some models\ncan carry more than one weapon – where this is the case, both\nWeapon Profiles should be noted on their Model Entry, one above\nthe other.\n★\tTYPE gives the weapon a broad description, fitting it into one\nof five categories: Melee, Pistol, Rifle, Heavy, and Grenade.\nMost weapons also show a Range in parentheses after their\nType, for example Rifle (18\").\n★\tTEST shows the S.P.E.C.I.A.L. Test that is made when\nattacking with this weapon. Tests are explained later.\n★\tTRAITS are special rules that apply to the model carrying\nthe weapon, usually when they make an attack with it.\n★\tCRITICAL EFFECT is a powerful special rule that can be\ntriggered if a player makes a lucky dice roll during an attack.\nROLLING DICE\nWhenever an outcome is uncertain, it is resolved by rolling dice.\nFallout: Factions uses two types of dice: Standard Dice and Luck\nDice. The two types should be visibly distinct from each other,\nbut both are normal ten-sided dice, marked from 1 to 10. The two\ntypes should be kept separate during the game. Standard Dice\nare used for most situations, while Luck Dice are only required\nwhen making a S.P.E.C.I.A.L. Test (as described below).\nRolling low is usually better than rolling high, so a 1 is the best\nresult and a 10 is the worst."
  },
  {
    "page": 15,
    "text": "15\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nBottle: Uh, hey, Cappy, if you make these\nTests all the time, what’s so special about them?\nCappy: Not special, Bottle – S.P.E.C.I.A.L.!\nStrength, Perception, Endurance, Charisma,\nIntelligence, Agility, and Luck. It’s a really handy way to\nmeasure what someone’s good at.\nBottle: Oh, now I get it!\nS.P.E.C.I.A.L. TESTS\nThe most common way for dice to be rolled is as part of a\nS.P.E.C.I.A.L. Test. This is called for whenever a model attempts\nto do something with an uncertain outcome, such as firing a pistol,\nswinging a baseball bat or trying to hack a computer terminal. A\nplayer rolls a number of dice and compares the result to one of the\nmodel’s S.P.E.C.I.A.L. statistics to determine the outcome.\nStatistic value is a Hit. Any other dice are Duds, and are\nremoved from the Pool.\nDice that score a 10 always count as Duds, regardless of the Test\nStatistic value.\n★\tIf all of the dice are removed as Duds, the Test is Failed – skip\nto step 5.\n★\tIf there is at least one Hit, the Test is Passed – continue to the\nnext step.\n3. Fortune Smiles\nFor each Luck Die remaining in the Pool, roll a Standard Die.\nEach die that scores equal to or lower than the model’s Test\nStatistic value is added to the Pool as an additional Hit. (Any dice\nthat score higher are ignored.)\n4. Trigger Critical Effect\nThis step is only used when making an Attack Test. When\nmaking any other kind of Test, skip this step.\nIf there is at least one Luck Die remaining in the Pool, the\nCritical Effect of the weapon being used in the attack is triggered.\nThe player making the Test resolves the Critical Effect, following\nthe rules listed on pg. 69.\nIf a weapon does not have a Critical Effect, skip this step. If a\nweapon has more than one Critical Effect, the player chooses only\none to resolve.\n5. Determine the Outcome\nThe rules that called for the Test explain what happens if the\nTest is Passed or Failed. Resolve this now.\nSometimes, it is enough to know that a model has Passed, but\nsometimes the outcome is determined by the number of Hits in\nthe Pool.\nA S.P.E.C.I.A.L.Test always has a name – for example, an Attack\nTest or a Confusion Test. This allows other rules to refer to that\nspecific type of Test. The Test’s name is followed by a number\nshowing the Pool Size (the number of dice that are rolled) and a\nletter showing the Test Statistic (the S.P.E.C.I.A.L. statistic used).\nFor example, when the rules say, “make an Evade Test (3A)”, the\nplayer rolls three dice and compares them to the model’s Agility.\nSometimes, the rules show an X in parentheses after a Test’s\nname, such as “make an Attack Test (X)”. This means that the\nPool Size and Test Statistics are variable, and the rules explain\nhow to determine them.\nTo make a S.P.E.C.I.A.L. Test, follow this sequence:\n1. Create the Pool\nCreate the Pool by gathering a number of dice equal to the Pool\nSize. First, gather a number of Luck Dice equal to the model’s\nLuck statistic.\nThen, add Standard Dice until the number of dice in the Pool\nequals the Pool Size. If the Pool Size is lower than the model’s\nLuck statistic, remove Luck Dice instead of adding Standard Dice\nto the Pool Size.\n2. Roll the Pool and Remove Duds\nRoll all of the dice in the Pool.\nAny die that scores equal to or lower than the model’s Test\nBonus Dice\nSome rules grant Bonus Dice to a Test. Each Bonus Die\nincreases the Pool Size by 1, for the purposes of that specific\nTest at the time.\nExperience: Failing Forward\nThe first time in each game that a player Fails a S.P.E.C.I.A.L.\nTest, their crew earns 1 Experience, as explained on pg. 38.\nA crew can only benefit from this rule once per game.\nUNLUCKY TESTS\nSome S.P.E.C.I.A.L. Tests are noted as being Unlucky.\nUnlucky Tests can never benefit from Bonus Dice, so their\nPool Size cannot be increased beyond the default value for\nthe Test.\nThey also skip the Fortune Smiles and Trigger Critical Effect\nsteps of the sequence – in effect, Luck Dice are treated as\nStandard Dice in an Unlucky Test."
  },
  {
    "page": 16,
    "text": "16\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nEXAMPLE ONE\nEXAMPLE TWO\nS.P.E.C.I.A.L. TEST EXAMPLES\nPete’s Psycho, Karve, is swinging a Machete at Sophie’s\nScavver, Eddie. The rules tell him to “make an Attack Test\n(4S)” for Karve. This means the Pool Size is 4 dice, and the Test\nwill use Karve’s Strength of 5.\nFirst, Pete creates the Pool. Karve has a Luck of 2, so he\ngathers 2 Luck Dice; he then adds 2 Standard Dice to bring the\ntotal number up to a Pool Size of 4.\nHe rolls the pool, scoring a 1 (Hit) and a 7 (Dud) on the Luck\nDice, and a 5 (Hit) and a 10 (Dud) on the Standard Dice. Pete\nremoves the Duds, leaving 2 Hits. Karve has passed the Test, so\nthe attack hits. Pete continues to step 3, to see how effective the\nhit is.\nAs there’s one Luck Die left in the Pool, Pete rolls another\nStandard Die, scoring a 4. If he’d rolled higher than Karve’s\nStrength he would discard the die, but instead he adds it to the\nPool, giving him a total of 4 Hits.\nAs he rolled at least one additional die, he also triggers the\nMachete’s Critical Effect, but we won’t worry about this for now.\nNow, Pete resolves the attack’s damage – which we will cover later.\nIt’s Sophie’s Turn, and she’s planning to return the favor. Her\nWaster, Slick Rick, opens fire at Karve with his rapid-firing\nHandmade Rifle. The rules say that the Test is Unlucky, as\nKarve is outside the weapon’s Effective Range, but Sophie\ndecides it’s still worth a shot.\nThis is an Attack Test (4P), so the Pool Size is 4 and the Test\nuses Rick’s Perception of 4. As the Test is Unlucky, Sophie can’t\ndo anything clever to gain Bonus Dice. She gathers 1 Luck Die\n(Rick has Luck 1) and 3 Standard Dice, and rolls them.\nShe scores a 2 on the Luck Die, and a 4, 5, and 8 on the\nStandard Dice. The 2 and 4 are Hits, but the 5 and 8 are Duds,\nso Sophie removes them. The attack is on target, but it’s not as\neffective as she was hoping!\nBecause the Test is Unlucky, she skips straight to the last step\nof the sequence. Even though there’s a Luck Die left in the Pool,\nthe attack sequence ends with 2 Hits and no Critical Effect.\nRemember - the dice included in this set,\nand shown above, have an icon in place of\nthe 1 - Bottle on the Luck Dice, and Cappy\non the Standard Dice."
