    "page": 17,
    "text": "17\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nDesigner’s Note: Unstable Models\nEXAMPLE: MEASUREMENT\nROLLING OFF AND RE-ROLLS\nSometimes, the rules instruct players to Roll Off. To do this, each\nplayer rolls a single die; the player with the lowest score wins the\nRoll Off. In the case of a tie, roll again. Remember: most ten-sided\ndice use a 0 on the tenth face, but this game treats it as being a 10.\nRules may also allow players to Re-roll dice. This lets them pick\nup any number of dice they have just rolled and roll them again.\nThe new result replaces the old one.\nOnly one Re-roll can be made per Test. When a player Re-rolls\ndice that are part of a Pool, they must decide how many dice they\nwill Re-roll before they Re-roll any of them.\nGAMEPLAY BASICS\nEach model is made up of a dynamically posed miniature mounted\non a circular Base.\nMEASURING DISTANCES\nAll distances in Fallout: Factions are measured in inches (\"). This\nstarter set contains a retractable measuring tape, marked in inches.\nMeasurements are always made from directly above, meaning\nthat differences in height do not matter, and only horizontal\ndistance is counted when measuring between two points.\nWhen measuring to or from a model, measure to or from the closest\nedge of its Base. Similarly, any distances measured to or from a\nToken are measured to or from its closest edge. Players are allowed\nto check measurements and distances whenever they like.\nWith a Battlefield full of evocative Terrain, you might want\nto position one of your models in a tricky place. Maybe it\nwon’t sit flat, maybe the Base doesn’t quite fit into a gap\nthat’s otherwise big enough for the model. The rules can’t\nlegislate for every single situation because every Terrain\ncollection is different.\nIf a model won’t fit where you’re trying to place it, or keeps\nfalling over, the most sensible thing is to put it somewhere\nelse. If you really want it to be there, and your opponent\nagrees that the model should be able to be there, place the\nmodel as close as possible but count it as occupying the\nchosen spot. You’ll need to make a judgement call when it\ncomes to Visibility (explained below). Most importantly,\nremember the Park Rules (pg.8) and don’t exploit this to\nyour advantage!\nPOSITIONING MODELS\nDuring play, models are positioned across the Battlefield, either\nat ground level or on top of Terrain Features. Models must always\nbe positioned so that they are standing up, with their Base\nentirely within the bounds of the Battlefield. They cannot be\nplaced so that their Base rests on top of another model’s Base.\nA model’s Base must always be as level as possible with the\nplaying surface – ideally it should sit flat, but this is not\nalways possible with detailed Terrain Features. A model can\nbe positioned so that part of its Base hangs over the edge of a\nTerrain Feature on which it is standing, as long as less than half\nof the base is overhanging.\nHere, the distance between the Boss and the Waster is 4\".\nThe measurements are taken between the closest edges of the\nmodels’ Bases, ignoring any protruding weapons.\nIn this example, the models are 8\" apart. They’re at different\nheights, but this doesn’t mean you measure diagonally."
