    "page": 18,
    "text": "18\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nDesigner’s Note: Area denial\nEXAMPLE: MEASURING MOVEMENT\nThe Proximity rules let you block access to areas of the\nBattlefield. You can place a model at the mouth of a narrow\nalleyway, knowing that Enemies can’t sneak past unless one\nof them Engages your model. You can also use these rules\nto protect your Champions – a couple of Grunts can run\ninterference, and your opponent will have to pin them down\nfirst before they can charge into your Leader!\nENGAGEMENT AND PROXIMITY\nIf two models from different crews are positioned so that their Bases\ntouch, they are Engaged with each other. This has a number of\neffects, such as determining the Actions that are available to them.\nEach Unengaged model is surrounded by an area that extends\n1\" out from its Base. This is the model’s Proximity. A model\ncan only enter an Enemy model’s Proximity if it is moving into\nEngagement with that model (see Moving Models).\nOnce a model is Engaged it loses its Proximity, and Enemy\nmodels can move past it freely. Note that models are unaffected\nby the Proximity of Friendly models.\nOddball Cases\nA model’s Proximity does not extend through solid walls that are\nat least as tall as the model. This means that it can be possible\nfor two models to be within 1\" of each other without being\nEngaged if there is a solid wall between them.\nModels whose Bases are at different heights can still be Engaged,\nas long as the elevated model’s Base is no higher than the\nuppermost point of the lower model (ignoring the lower model’s\nweapons, equipment, and protruding pieces of clothing, such as\nthe horns on a Pack Top Dog’s helmet).\nMOVING MODELS\nVarious rules let players move their models around the Battlefield.\nThese rules always give the maximum distance in inches that the\nmodel can move. When moving a model, move it in a straight line,\nmeasuring to and from the same point on its Base.\nPlayers can break a model's move down into multiple smaller\nmoves, as long as the total distance traveled does not exceed the\nmaximum distance allowed.\nA model can move through Friendly models freely, but cannot\nenter an Enemy's Proximity (see above) unless it ends its move\nEngaged with that model.\nHere, the Operators player wants to move their Boss forward\n5\". They pick a point on the Base – the front – then pick it up\nand move the model so that the same point is 5\" away.\nThis ensures that the model moves 5\" – no more, no less.\nHere, the player’s not being consistent. They start measuring\nfrom the front of the Boss’ Base, then move the model so that\nthe back of its Base is 5\" away – which means the Boss has\nmoved too far!\nThis player started measuring from the back of the Boss'\nBase, then moved it so that the front of its Base is 5\" away. If\nthey count this a 5\" move, they've short-changed themselves."
