    "page": 19,
    "text": "19\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nEXAMPLE: CLIMBIMG\nCROSSING GAPS\nDuring a move, a model can cross any gaps that are no wider than\nits Base. If a gap is any wider, the model cannot move across it.\nCLIMBING UP AND DOWN\nA model can climb up or down a Terrain Feature to reach a\nhigher or lower level. When it does so, the difference in elevation\n(i.e., the vertical distance the model moves) is counted towards\nits movement distance. Note that this is an exception to the\nstandard rules, where only horizontal distance is measured.\nA model can only climb up to a higher level if there is a Terrain\nFeature to climb (for example, a wall, a rope ladder, or the side\nof a vehicle). It can drop down without a Terrain Feature (for\nexample, leaping over the side of a raised walkway), but if the\ndifference in elevation is greater than the model’s Agility in\ninches, its move ends as soon as it reaches the lower level.\nEdge Cases\nDifferences in elevation of less than an inch are not counted\ntowards a model’s movement distance, and neither are small\nobstacles up to an inch tall. Similarly, when a model climbs a\nslope or staircase, the elevation change is disregarded. Vertical\ndistance should only be counted when a model moves in such a\nway where they would feasibly have to shoulder their weapons\nand put their hands to use.\nThe Pack player wants to move their Scavver up onto this\nTerrain Feature. The total horizontal distance moved is 6\", but\nit includes a change in elevation of 2\". This is counted towards\nthe movement distance, so the Scavver has moved 8\".\nHere, the Pack player wants their Scavver to move down\nfrom this (much taller!) Terrain Feature. The total horizontal\nmovement distance is 2\", but the elevation change is 5\",\nmeaning the total movement distance is 7\".\nHowever, the Scavver only has an Agility of 4, and the overhang\nmeans there’s nothing for them to climb down – they’ll have to\ndrop down instead. The change in elevation is greater than their\nAgility, so their move will end here even if the Pack player would\nnormally be allowed to move the model a greater distance.\nThe Scavver moves across an obstacle then clambers up to a\nslightly higher level. As both elevation changes are under an\ninch, no vertical movement is counted, and the Scavver counts\nas having only moved the horizontal distance of 6\"."
