    "page": 20,
    "text": "20\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nWeary Token\nExhausted\nToken\nEXAMPLE: CONTROL AREA\nVISIBILITY\nSome rules (especially the rules for making Ranged Attacks) ask\nwhether a model is Visible to another model.\nOne model can see another if an imaginary line can be traced\nfrom its head to any part of the other model. A model’s Base is\nignored when determining Visibility, as are weapons, equipment,\nand protruding pieces of clothing, such as the horns on a Pack Top\nDog’s helmet.\nThis line cannot be traced through other models, or through\nTerrain Features (except Decorative Features). However, a line\ndoes not have to be traced to every part of the model; as long as\nit can be traced to one part of it, the model is Visible.\nFATIGUE AND EXHAUSTION\nDuring play, models can gain Fatigue in two main ways:\n★\tA model can take Fatigue by performing an Action or\ngaining a bonus.\n★\tA model can suffer Fatigue. This usually happens as a\nnegative consequence, or as the result of an Action by an\nEnemy model as the result of a rule.\nA model’s Fatigue is shown by placing\nFatigue Tokens next to its Base. The\nWeary side of the Token is used to show\nthat a model has taken 1 Fatigue, and the\nExhausted side of the Token is used to show\nthat a model has taken 2 Fatigue.\nA model that is Exhausted cannot gain any\nmore Fatigue. This means it cannot Take\nFatigue, so cannot perform any Actions or\ngain any bonuses that would require it to do\nso. If anything causes an Exhausted model to\nSuffer Fatigue, the extra Fatigue is ignored.\nAll Fatigue Tokens are removed at the end of each Round, but\nsome rules allow models to Recover Fatigue before then.\nCappy: The easiest way to check visibility is to\nget a model's eye view. Put yourself at eye-level\nbehind the model and see what you can see\nfrom its perspective!\nBottle: And remember – if in doubt – refer to the Park Rules on\npage 8!\nThe Disciples Waster in the center of this image has a\nCharisma of 3, so its Control Area extends 3\" out from its\nBase in all directions.\nThe Butcher is too far away to be in the Control Area, and\nthe Pack Psycho is an Enemy model, but the other two\nmodels (the Psycho and the Tormentor) are both in the\nWaster's Control Area.\nWIDE OPEN AND OBSCURED\nWhen models make Ranged Attacks (as described on page 25), the\nrules refer to Targets that are both Wide Open and those that\nare Obscured.\nWhen checking Visibility, a model is Wide Open if a line can be\ntraced to all parts of it (not counting its Base or any Ignored\nparts). This gives a bonus to the attack. Remember that\nDecorative Terrain Features are always entirely Ignored, so can\nbe moved aside when checking if a model is Wide Open.\nA model is Obscured if any part of it is hidden by any part of\nanother model from the same crew. This will make it harder to\nselect the model as the Target of a Ranged Attack.\nCONTROL AREA\nDuring play, models can give orders to Friendly models around\nthem, bringing them along when they move or getting support\nwhen they make a Ranged Attack. This is represented by the\nmodel’s Control Area.\nA model’s Control Area extends out from its Base a number of\ninches equal to its Charisma. All Friendly models within this\narea count as being within the model’s Control Area."
