    "text": "23\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nHurrying\nThe Active player can declare that the Active model and/or any\nmodels given Movement Orders can Hurry. When a model\nHurries, it takes an additional Fatigue but can move up to 12\"\ninstead of up to 8\".\nACTION: OPEN FIRE (UNENGAGED MODELS)\nThe Active player chooses a Pistol, Rifle, Heavy or Grenade\nweapon that the Active model is carrying, then follows these\nsteps to make a Ranged Attack:\n1. Choose Target\nThe Active player chooses a Target for the attack. This must be\nan Enemy model that is Visible to the Active model.\nIf the Active model’s view of the Target is Obscured (see pg. 20),\nthe opposing player can declare that the Obscuring model is\nBlocking the Shot. The Active player must either target the\nObscuring model, or choose a different Target.\n2. Declare Supporting Fire\nThe Active player can choose a number of their other Unengaged\nmodels within the Active model’s Control Area and declare\nthat they will give Supporting Fire. Each model that gives\nSupporting Fire must take Fatigue to do so. The maximum\nnumber of models that can give Supporting Fire is equal to the\nActive model’s Charisma value – so a model with a Charisma of 3\ncan be supported by up to 3 other models.\nA model can only provide Supporting Fire if the intended Target\nis both Visible and not Obscured to the attacking model. The\ndistance to the Target must be no greater than the Range value of\na Pistol or Rifle weapon carried by the model.\nUNENGAGED\nMODELS\nGet Moving\nThe model moves, and can give\nother models around it orders to do\nthe same.\nOpen Fire\nThe model targets a visible Enemy\nwith a Ranged Attack.\nPatch Up\nThe model takes a moment to\nrecuperate.\nRummage\nThe model looks for helpful items\nat a Search Token. This Action is\npart of the Advanced Rules, and is\ndetailed on pg. 26.\nENGAGED\nMODELS\nBack Off\nThe model disengages from the\nEnemy.\nBrawl\nThe model targets an Engaged\nEnemy with a Melee Attack.\nPassing\nBefore their Turn starts, a player can declare that they will Pass.\nThis means they will not take this Turn, or any more Turns this\nRound. A player must declare that they will Pass if they are\nunable to make any Actions (for example, if all of their models are\nExhausted), but can Pass before this point if they wish.\nWhen a player Passes, they take the Initiative Token (or keep it,\nif they already had it). The other crew then takes any number of\nTurns in a row; once they no longer wish to take any more Turns,\nthe Round is over. (Note that this does not count as the second\nplayer Passing, so they do not take the Initiative Token.)\nACTIONS\nDuring a Turn, the Active model can make one or more Actions. At\nthe start of each Action it makes, the Active model takes Fatigue.\nThere are a number of different Actions available, each of which\nlets the Active model do something different. The Actions available\nto a model depend on whether or not it is Engaged (see pg. 18).\nUnless a rule specifically states otherwise, a model cannot make\nthe same Action more than once per Turn.\nACTION: GET MOVING (UNENGAGED MODELS)\nThe Active player moves the Active model up to 8\".\nMovement Orders\nAt the start of a Get Moving Action, the Active player can choose\na number of their other Unengaged models within the Active\nmodel’s Control Area, and give them Movement Orders as part\nof the same Action.\nEach model that is given Movement Orders must take Fatigue.\nThe Active player can then move them up to 8\" at the same time\nthat they move the Active model.\nWEAPON RANGES\nMost weapons have a Range in inches listed after their\nType – for example, Pistol (8\"). This value is the Effective\nRange of the weapon. When a model makes an attack with\none of these weapons, the Test is Unlucky if the distance to\nthe Target is greater than the listed Range.\nWeapons with the CQB (Close-Quarters-Battle) Trait are\nintended for close-range combat, and cannot be used if the\nTarget is outside their Effective Range."
  },
