    "page": 24,
    "text": "24\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nDesigner’s Note: other actions\n3. Make the Attack Test\nThe Active player makes an Attack Test (X), using the Test\nvalue from the chosen weapon’s profile to determine the Pool Size\nand Test Statistic.\nThe Test has the following Bonus Dice:\n★\tAdd one Bonus Die for each model that is giving Supporting\nFire.\n★\tAdd one Bonus Die for each Harm the Target has (see pg. 21).\n★\tAdd one Bonus Die if the Target is Wide Open (see pg. 20).\nIf the Test is Failed, the attack deals no damage and the Action\nends. If the Test is Passed, continue to the next step.\n4. Inflict Damage\nInflict Damage on the Target equal to the number of Hits in the\nPool, as described on pg. 21.\nACTION: PATCH UP (UNENGAGED MODELS)\nThe Active model recovers up to 2 Harm (see pg. 21).\nACTION: BACK OFF (ENGAGED MODELS)\nThe Active player moves the Active model up to 2\". It cannot end\nthis move within an enemy model’s Proximity.\nACTION: BRAWL (ENGAGED MODELS)\nThe Active player chooses a Melee weapon that the Active\nmodel carries (or declares that it will use a Makeshift Weapon\nas described below), then follows these steps to make a Melee\nAttack:\n1. Choose Target\nThe Active player chooses a Target for the attack. This must be an\nEnemy model that is Engaged with the Active model.\n2. Make the Attack Test\nThe Active player makes an Attack Test (X), using the Test\nvalue from the chosen weapon’s profile to determine the Pool Size\nand Test Statistic.\nThe Test has the following Bonus Dice:\n★\tAdd one Bonus Die if the Active model moved into\nEngagement with the Target this Turn.\n★\tAdd one Bonus Die for each Harm the Target has (see pg. 21).\n★\tAdd one Bonus Die for each other Friendly model that is\nEngaged with the Target and is not Engaged with any other\nEnemy models.\n3. Inflict Damage\nInflict Damage on the Target equal to the number of Hits in the\nPool, as described on pg. 21.\nSome rules allow models to make Actions that aren’t listed\nhere. For example, in the Advanced Rules, Unengaged\nmodels can make Rummage Actions (Pg. 26) to scavenge for\nCaps and Chems in piles of Wasteland debris.\nWhenever a new Action is introduced, the rules explain\nhow to use it, and whether it can be made by an Engaged or\nUnengaged model.\nBottle: Hold it there, folks!\nCappy: If you’ve read this far, you already\nknow enough to play your first game …\nBottle: … so, what are you waiting for?\nCappy: Take a look at the Welcome to Nuka-World booklet for\nan easy first Scenario and two ready-made sample crews that will\nlet you jump right into the action!\nBottle: The rest of this chapter will make a lot\nmore sense if you’ve already tried out the rules.\nMAKESHIFT WEAPONS\nEvery model that is not carrying another Melee weapon is\nassumed to be carrying a Makeshift Weapon, whether or not\nit is shown on the miniature.\nTYPE\nTEST\nTRAITS\nEFFECT\nMakeshift Weapon\nMelee\nS2\n-\n-\n\n\nA Makeshift Weapon might represent an improvised blade, a\nhunk of wreckage, a length of pipe, the butt of a weapon, or\nthe model’s fists.\nWORKHORSE WEAPONS\nSupporting Fire represents other crew members opening\nup with sporadic bursts to put pressure on the target.\nGrenades and heavy weapons are too precious to be used so\nhaphazardly, which is why the target has to be within range\nof a pistol or rifle carried by the supporting model."
