    "page": 26,
    "text": "26\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nDesigner’s Note: Floating Chems\nRADIATION TOKENS\nPockets of radiation are a hazard of the\nWasteland, and Nuka-World is no different.\nIt is represented on the Battlefield by\nRadiation Tokens. These Tokens cannot\nbe moved once they have been placed, but\nthey are ignored entirely for the purposes of\nVisibility and Movement.\nWhile a model is within 3\" of a Radiation Token, its Endurance is\ncounted as being one point lower, to a minimum of 1. If a model is\nwithin 3\" of multiple Radiation Tokens, this penalty is cumulative.\nPLOYS\nWinning a battle doesn’t just come down to\ntactics and luck. Shrewd commanders think\nstrategically and plan devastating surprises\nfor their opponents. In Fallout: Factions, these\none-use surprises come in the form of Ploys.\nThe number of Ploys a crew can enact per game is strictly limited.\nAt the start of the Scenario, each player takes a number of Ploy\nTokens equal to their crew’s Tier. They must discard a Ploy Token\nto enact a Ploy.\nA crew can never use the same Ploy more than once during a\ngame (with the exception of Lucky Break, as shown below).\nACTION: RUMMAGE (UNENGAGED MODELS)\nThe Active player chooses a Search Token within 1\" of the\nActive model and rolls two dice. They then choose one of the\nfollowing options:\n★\tFind a Chem: Choose a Common Chem with a Cap cost\nno higher than the total of the two dice, and add one dose\nof it to the Crew’s Roster. Alternatively, if the total of the\ntwo dice was 18 or higher, add one dose of a Rare Chem\nto the Crew’s Roster.\n★\tFind Caps and Parts: The die that scored higher is how\nmany Caps are found. The die that scored lower is how\nmany Parts are found. Add both to the crew’s Stash.\nThen, if either of the dice scored a 10, replace the Search\nToken with a Radiation Token. Otherwise, remove the Search\nToken from play.\nSCOUT: STASHED GOODS\nAfter rolling the dice, the player can spend a Scouting Point\n(Pg. 43) to Re-roll one die, or 2 Scouting Points to Re-roll\nboth dice.\nPloy: Teamwork\nEnact this Ploy at the end of your crew’s Turn. Immediately\ntake another Turn. You must choose a different Active model.\nPloy: Second Wind\nEnact this Ploy at the start of your crew’s Turn. Pick an\nExhausted model in your crew to be the Active model for this\nTurn. It immediately recovers 1 Fatigue.\nPloy: Lucky Break\nEnact this Ploy after making a S.P.E.C.I.A.L. Test for a\nmodel in your crew after the dice have been rolled, but before\nthe Fortune Smiles step: Re-roll all of the Duds in the pool.\nUnlike other Ploys, Lucky Break can be used more than once\nduring a game, but never more than once on a single Test.\nBottle: Gee, Cappy, Ploys are a lot of fun!\nCappy: They sure are, Bottle! A well-used\nPloy can make a huge difference in a game.\nJust remember – you don’t have to choose the\nPloy you’ll use until you want to use it, so you can keep your\noptions open!\nBottle: And once you’ve used a Ploy, you can’t use it again, no\nmatter how much you might want to.\nIt’s important to note that you don’t need to know which\nmodels are carrying which Chems until you want to use\nthem. And yes, a Scavver can find some Nuka-Cola with\na Rummage Action, and a Psycho on the other side of the\nBattlefield can use it!\nThis is a small abstraction that saves record-keeping, lets\nthe game flow smoothly, and ensures that Chems are always\navailable to use.\nPloy token\nRadiation\ntoken\nSTANDARD PLOYS\nAll crews have access to the three Standard Ploys listed below.\nIn addition, a crew has access to a series of Ploys that are unique\nto its Faction (see the Faction Lists in Appendix 2, pg. 55, 58 and\n61), and some Scenarios will give one or both crews access to\nadditional Ploys."
  },
  {
    "page": 27,
    "text": "27\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nDry Rock Gulch\nRETREATING\nA crew should always know when it’s time to hit the road.\nConceding a single battle is better than losing half your crew!\nWhen a player declares that they Pass, they can also declare\nthat they will Retreat. They take the Initiative Token as\nnormal, but flip it upside down to its “Retreat” side. At the end\nof the current Round, all of the crew’s models are removed from\nplay, and the game ends – even if there are still face-up Round\nTracker Tokens.\nGIFT-WRAPPED GOODS\nAt the end of the game, if one crew has Retreated, the other\nplayer rolls 2 dice for each Search Token that remains on the\nBattlefield. For each roll, the higher die shows how many Caps\ntheir crew finds, and the lower die shows how many Parts they\nfind. Add any Caps and Parts to the crew’s Stash.\nSCOUTING LOCATIONS\nIn the Story Phase (see pg. 40), players will be able to Scout\nLocations. When they do so, they will record a number of\nScouting Points next to the Location on the Story Sheet of\ntheir Crew Roster.\nA player can spend Scouting Points in three ways, and some\nScenarios or special rules may offer additional ways to spend\nScouting Points. In either case, players can only spend Scouting\nPoints from the game’s current Location.\nScout: Scenario Choice\nPlayers can spend Scouting Points when determining which\nScenario will be played, as described on pg. 34.\nScout: Repositioning\nBefore the first Round of a game begins, the players can take\nTurns to spend Scouting Points to reposition a model. The\nplayer with the Cappy Token goes first, then their opponent.\nWhen repositioning a model, the Controlling player can move\nit up to 3\". It can move outside of its Start Area, but cannot\nenter the opponent’s Start Area. Repositioning the first\nmodel costs 1 Scouting Point, the second costs 2 points, and\nso on. Each model can only be repositioned once.\nIf a player Passes their Turn, or does not have enough\nScouting Points to spend, they do not take any further Turns\n– the other player finishes repositioning any models they\nwish, then the first Round begins.\nScout: Stashed Goods\nAfter rolling the dice for a Rummage Action (pg. 26), a player\ncan spend a Scouting Point to Re-roll one die, or 2 Scouting\nPoints to Re-roll both dice.\nOPTIONAL RULE:\n\nEXPANDED LOCATIONS\nEach game of Fallout: Factions is set in a specific Location – one\nof the five themed parks around Nuka-World. In the standard\nrules, the Location only really affects the game’s Setup and\nOutcome, but the following rules allow players to add some more\nthematic flavor.\nThese rules are only used if both players agree to use them, and\ncannot be used in games that take place in the Wasteland.\nLOCATION-SPECIFIC CHEMS\nWhen a model makes a Rummage Action (see pg. 26), they can\nadd a dose of the Rare Chem listed below if the total of the two\ndice is at least 15, rather than 18. Each crew can do this once\nper game.\n\n★ In Galaxy Zone, the Rare Chem is Psycho Jet.\n\n★ In Dry Rock Gulch, the Rare Chem is Whiskey.\n\n★ In Safari Adventure, the Rare Chem is Med-X.\n\n★ In World of Refreshment, the Rare Chem is Nuka-Cola Dark.\n\n★ In Kiddie Kingdom, the Rare Chem is Day Tripper.\nLOCATION-SPECIFIC PLOYS\nIf both players wish to do so, they can also use these Location-\nSpecific Ploys. The decision to do so must be made before\ndeciding in which Location the game will take place. These rules\nare only used if both players agree to use them.\nWhen these rules are in effect, each Location has two additional\nPloys that either player can choose from when playing a game in\nthat Location."
  },
  {
    "page": 28,
    "text": "28\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nGALACTIC ZONE\nWith aliens and robots aplenty, there’s always fun\nto be found at The Galactic Zone! Where rockets\n(propelling both grenades and fun!) fly overhead,\nlasers light up the sky, and you can embark on brand new\nadventures to save the known galaxy! Bring your best blaster,\nstrap on your space suit, and get ready to blast off!\nKill the Lights\nThese old circuit breakers aren’t hard to trip.\nEnact this Ploy at the start of any Round. Until the end of\nthe Round, each model’s Visibility is limited to double their\nPerception value, in inches. For example, a model with Perception\n4 can see up to 8\". Models cannot make Ranged Attacks or give\nSupporting Fire if the Target is outside this distance.\nPatrolling Nukatron\nA great many robots patrol the Galactic Zone; it was just a\nmatter of time before one wandered by.\nEnact this Ploy at the start of any Round. Position a Nukatron\nmodel (or a stand-in on a standard-sized Base) so that the edge\nof its Base is in contact with any edge of the Battlefield. It uses\nthe Profile below.\nOn the Round in which it is placed, the player that enacted this\nPloy controls the Nukatron. It can only make Get Moving, Open\nFire and Brawl Actions. It has no Control Area, and it cannot\nmake use of Chems. In each subsequent Round, the player with\nthe Initiative Token controls the Nukatron.\nThe Nukatron counts as an Enemy model to both crews, and\ncan therefore be attacked by models from either side, no matter\nwhich player controls it in a given Round. If it is Incapacitated,\nit is removed from play and replaced with a Search Token.\nS\nP\nE\nC\nI\nA\nL\n♥\nWEAPON\nTYPE\nTEST\nTRAITS\nEFFECT\n4\n5\n6\n0\n1\n2\n1\n1\nNukatron Lasers\nRifle (16\")\n4P\nFast\nSuppress (1)"
  },
  {
    "page": 29,
    "text": "29\nFALLOUT: FACTIONS – BATTLE FOR NUKA-WORLD | 02: Building Blocks\nDRY ROCK GULCH\nAin’t no need for those fancy laser guns ‘ere partner!\nA six-shooter, glass of whiskey, cowboy hat, and\nexplorer's spirit ‘s’all you need to call Dry Rock\nGulch home. Just be aware, at high noon all sorts of gunslingers\ncome a-callin', so best keep your finger on that trigger…\nBloodworm Attack\nThis whole part of the park is swarming with Bloodworms,\nwaiting for their chance to strike.\nEnact this Ploy during the opposing crew’s Turn, at the end of\na Get Moving Action they have made. Pick an Enemy model\nthat moved during this Action, and is on ground level (not on a\nTerrain Feature). This model, and each other model within 3\" of\nit that is also on ground level, is attacked by Bloodworms.\nMake an Evade Test (3A) for each model that is attacked.\nThe model suffers 3 Damage, minus 1 for each Hit scored. (For\nexample, if they score 2 Hits, the model suffers 1 Damage.)\nHigh Noon Shootout\nStand out in the open, narrow your eyes, and draw!\nEnact this Ploy at the start of any of your Turns. Until the end\nof the Round, each of your models that makes a Ranged Attack\nagainst a Wide Open Target gains 2 Bonus Dice instead of 1.\nIn addition, until the end of the Round, your models do not have\nto take Confusion Tests if one of your models is Incapacitated by\na Ranged Attack that gains the Wide Open bonus.\nSAFARI ADVENTURE\nFrom the Angry Anaconda to Cappy’s very own\nhome away from home, come and wander through\nyour very own Safari Adventure! With over 100\ndifferent and exotic animals, you never know what you’ll see\naround the next corner!\nGatorclaw Roar\nA ravenous Gatorclaw is hunting in the vicinity, and its roar is\nenough to send even the most hardened Raider running.\nEnact this Ploy at the start of any of your Turns. Pick a\nBattlefield Edge. Until the end of the Round, any model that is\nwithin 6\" of this edge when it makes a Confusion Test treats its\nIntelligence as 1 lower.\nA.F.A.D. Cache\nAn ancient cache of supplies has been found, abandoned by the\nAnimal Friends and Defenders.\nEnact this Ploy at the start of any of your Turns. If you have\nspace to do so, add one Med-X, one Stimpak, and one Buffout to\nyour Crew Roster.\nWORLD OF REFRESHMENT\nThis isn’t just a ride, it’s one of several operational\nfactories actively producing Nuka-Cola. Here\nin the mixing area, we combine just a hint of 17\nselect fruit flavors to produce that unique Nuka-Cola taste! Just\nremember: as tasty as the water looks on the Quantum River,\nbest keep your hands inside the vehicle at all times.\nA Crate of Cold Ones\nWhat better place to stock up on Nuka-Cola?\nEnact this Ploy at the start of any of your Turns. If you have\nspace to do so, add two Nuka-Cola and one Nuka-Cola Dark to\nyour Crew Roster.\nAnimatronic Distraction\nAn animatronic remnant of the Bottling Plant tour springs to\nlife, causing a sudden distraction.\nEnact this Ploy when the other player gathers the Pool for an\nAttack Test.\nPlace a spare model on a standard-sized Base anywhere within\n5\" of the model for which the Test is being made. This represents\nthe animatronic. Any Tests made for models within 5\" of the\nanimatronic – including the one for the current attack – are treated\nas Unlucky. Remove the animatronic at the end of the Round.\nKIDDIE KINGDOM\nSpinning Cups, Ferris Wheels, and more mean fun\nis in the air at the Kiddie Kingdom! The staff of\nthe kingdom are on hand to cater to every whim of\nthe young royalty that grace our rides, and they’re so eager that\nthey’re practically crawling over one another to do so!\nFeral Ghoul Scavengers\nThe eerie denizens of Kiddie Kingdom lurk in the shadows,\nready to drag away the wounded …\nEnact this Ploy when an Enemy model suffers an Injury.\nThe model’s player makes an Evade Test (2E) for the model. If\nthe Test Fails, the model is removed from play. If it Passes, you\ndo not count as having used a Ploy, and can attempt to use this\nPloy again.\nRadioactive Sprayers\nKiddie Kingdom has a very effective form of defence: ancient\nwater sprayers, now brimming with deadly radiation.\nEnact this Ploy at the start of any Round after the first.\nPlace a Radiation Token anywhere on the battlefield that is not\nwithin 3\" of a Search Token, a model, an Objective Token, or\nanother Radiation Token. Then your opponent places a second\nRadiation Token, following the same rules. Finally, you place a\nthird and final Radiation Token in the same way."
  },
